The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Petition rejected

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Calcutta High Court on Friday rejected a petition demanding a compensation of Rs 50 lakh from Trinamul Congress, Congress and SUCI for damaging government property during the March 16 bandh. A division bench of Justice P.C. Ghosh and Justice B. Somadder held the petition was politically motivated.

 Exam: The practical test for computer application (additional) for Madhyamik students will be held on April 26 for the schools under the Calcutta regional office of the state board of secondary education. The test will be held a day before in schools under the North Bengal, Burdwan and Midnapore regional offices.

 Children injured: Five children, aged between seven and 14 years, were injured in Sonarpur, on the southern fringes of the city, when they set a matchstick to an unidentified powder near a pond. Three children with facial burns were taken to MR Bangur Hospital and the rest were admitted to a nursing home, police said. A probe has been ordered.

 Suicide: Sanjay Mallick, 27, an autorickshaw driver, committed suicide by hanging himself at his Nimtola house on Thursday night. He was taken to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital, where doctors pronounced him dead. Police said Mallik had been suffering from depression, as he could not afford the treatment of his wife, who has been afflicted with tuberculosis.

 Accident: Rajesh Jaiswal, 55, was injured after the motorcycle he was riding was hit by a taxi on the eastern slope of Howrah bridge on Friday morning. He was admitted to Medical College and Hospital. The taxi driver has been arrested and the vehicle impounded.

 Stamp show: A two-day philatelic show opened in Barasat, on the northern fringes of the city, on Friday. Rare stamps are on display at the exhibition.




